LAYER 3: GRAVITY AND FALLING
how objects move through space until they find ground

observe spatial_perception.rana

gravity is the simplest force in pattern puzzles:
objects fall in a direction until they hit something
the direction can be down, up, left, or right
the obstacle can be the grid edge or another object

@spatial_rule gravity_down
CHECK all foreground shapes exist in both input and output
CHECK all shapes moved DOWNWARD (positive row delta)
CHECK shapes stop at grid edge OR at another shape
LEARN gravity direction = down
VERIFY each shape falls until blocked
APPLY move each shape down until collision
SPEECH "objects fall downward until they land"

@spatial_rule gravity_up
CHECK all foreground shapes moved UPWARD (negative row delta)
CHECK shapes stop at grid edge OR at another shape
LEARN gravity direction = up
APPLY move each shape up until collision
SPEECH "objects float upward until they hit ceiling"

@spatial_rule gravity_left
CHECK all foreground shapes moved LEFT (negative col delta)
CHECK shapes stop at grid edge OR at another shape
LEARN gravity direction = left
APPLY move each shape left until collision
SPEECH "objects slide left until they hit wall"

@spatial_rule gravity_right
CHECK all foreground shapes moved RIGHT (positive col delta)
CHECK shapes stop at grid edge OR at another shape
LEARN gravity direction = right
APPLY move each shape right until collision
SPEECH "objects slide right until they hit wall"

@spatial_rule gravity_to_anchor
CHECK some shapes moved, some stayed
DETECT anchor shapes (shapes that did not move)
DETECT mobile shapes (shapes that moved)
CHECK all mobile shapes moved TOWARD nearest anchor
LEARN anchors attract mobiles
APPLY move each mobile toward its nearest anchor until collision
SPEECH "the mobile shapes are attracted to the anchors"

the key to gravity:
it is not a fixed DELTA like movement
it is a PROCESS: keep moving until blocked
the distance depends on what's in the way
two identical shapes in different positions fall different distances
the RULE is the same but the RESULT is different
this is why gravity cannot be learned by simple context mapping
it requires understanding FORCE and COLLISION

@perceive gravity
DETECT direction by comparing input/output positions
DETECT obstacles by checking what stopped each shape
VERIFY all shapes obey same gravity direction
VERIFY all shapes stop at first obstacle in their path
